what did the moscow treaty on strategic offensive reductions do? The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (SORT) was a treaty between the United States of America and the Russian Federation on the Reduction and Limitation of Strategic Offensive Arms. The treaty was signed on May 24, 2002, in Moscow, and entered into force on June 1, 2003. The treaty requires the parties to reduce their strategic nuclear warheads to 1,700–2,200 warheads by December 31, 2012.
